04664nam a22005535i 9780300147247DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20082008ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001472477 a10.12987/97803001472472doi  a(DE-B1597)485390  a(OCoLC)1024015907  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aHV9950b.U85 1999eb 7aLAW0000002bisacsh04a364/.089/009732211 aUviller, H. Richard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Tilted Playing Field :bIs Criminal Justice Unfair? /cH. Richard Uviller. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (326 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Metaphorically Speaking -- t1. Level Playing Fields and the Idea of Fairness -- t2. Discretion and the Advantage of Initiation: Choosing a Target Bringing a Charge -- t3. Access to Information, First- and Secondhand: You Are What You Know -- t4. Voucher and the Virtue of Office: The White-Hat Factor -- t5. Burdens and Presumptions: Rescue from the Quandary of Perhaps -- t6. The Blessing of Bankroll: Financial Disparity and the Riddle of Bail -- t7. Excluding Adverse Evidence: Truth or Justice? -- t8. Appealability and the Ordeal of Jeopardy: Capitalization of Error -- t9. Truth Telling and the Limits of Ethical License: Counsel’s Tolerable Deceptions -- t10. Jury Irrationality and Its Insulation: Arousing the Unimpeachable Impulse -- t11. Summary: The Fair Tilt -- tConclusion , if any -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlthough evenly matched adversaries make for a more exciting athletic contest, and a level playing field is essential to a fair game, is the same true in a criminal trial? In this compelling new book, H. Richard Uviller argues that a criminal trial is not analogous to a sporting event. Prosecutors and defense attorneys are, in critical respects, different from each other, and the allocation of advantages to each must be uneven in order to be fair.In a lively exploration of the powers of the prosecutor and the prerogatives of the defense, Uviller asks where our criminal justice system is fair though unequal and where its inequalities may subvert fair results. On the one hand, he points out, the prosecutor has unmatched and virtually unreviewable discretion to choose the target of a prosecution, the charge, and to a large extent the timing of an indictment. The prosecution also is first on the scene to develop evidence and is entitled to compel the production of evidence from reluctant custodians. The lawyer for the defendant, on the other hand, enjoys virtually unrestricted license to argue contrary to his or her own sincere belief, as well as broad powers to discover evidence from the prosecutor’s file. Are these unequal advantages necessary? Are they fair? Uviller concludes that although the overall criminal justice system reflects a fair distribution of advantages and disadvantages, in certain areas the imbalance is so severe as to undermine justice. He offers realistic, carefully considered recommendations for reform in these problem areas.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCriminal justice, Administration ofxMoral and ethical aspectszUnited States. 0aDiscrimination in criminal justice administrationzUnited States. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030007584740uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030014724740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300147247423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300147247/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale Uni